.TH ets 3 "stdlib 3.13.2" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
ets \- Built-in term storage.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.LP
This module is an interface to the Erlang built-in term storage BIFs\&. These provide the ability to store very large quantities of data in an Erlang runtime system, and to have constant access time to the data\&. (In the case of \fIordered_set\fR\&, see below, access time is proportional to the logarithm of the number of stored objects\&.)
.LP
Data is organized as a set of dynamic tables, which can store tuples\&. Each table is created by a process\&. When the process terminates, the table is automatically destroyed\&. Every table has access rights set at creation\&.
.LP
Tables are divided into four different types, \fIset\fR\&, \fIordered_set\fR\&, \fIbag\fR\&, and \fIduplicate_bag\fR\&\&. A \fIset\fR\& or \fIordered_set\fR\& table can only have one object associated with each key\&. A \fIbag\fR\& or \fIduplicate_bag\fR\& table can have many objects associated with each key\&.
.LP

.RS -4
.B
Note:
.RE
The number of tables stored at one Erlang node \fIused\fR\& to be limited\&. This is no longer the case (except by memory usage)\&. The previous default limit was about 1400 tables and could be increased by setting the environment variable \fIERL_MAX_ETS_TABLES\fR\& or the command line option \fI+e\fR\& before starting the Erlang runtime system\&. This hard limit has been removed, but it is currently useful to set the \fIERL_MAX_ETS_TABLES\fR\& anyway\&. It should be set to an approximate of the maximum amount of tables used\&. This since an internal table for named tables is sized using this value\&. If large amounts of named tables are used and \fIERL_MAX_ETS_TABLES\fR\& hasn\&'t been increased, the performance of named table lookup will degrade\&.

.LP
Notice that there is no automatic garbage collection for tables\&. Even if there are no references to a table from any process, it is not automatically destroyed unless the owner process terminates\&. To destroy a table explicitly, use function \fIdelete/1\fR\&\&. The default owner is the process that created the table\&. To transfer table ownership at process termination, use option \fIheir\fR\& or call \fIgive_away/3\fR\&\&.
.LP
Some implementation details:
.RS 2
.TP 2
*
In the current implementation, every object insert and look-up operation results in a copy of the object\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
\fI\&'$end_of_table\&'\fR\& is not to be used as a key, as this atom is used to mark the end of the table when using functions \fIfirst/1\fR\& and \fInext/2\fR\&\&.
.LP
.RE

.LP
Notice the subtle difference between \fImatching\fR\& and \fIcomparing equal\fR\&, which is demonstrated by table types \fIset\fR\& and \fIordered_set\fR\&:
.RS 2
.TP 2
*
Two Erlang terms \fImatch\fR\& if they are of the same type and have the same value, so that \fI1\fR\& matches \fI1\fR\&, but not \fI1\&.0\fR\& (as \fI1\&.0\fR\& is a \fIfloat()\fR\& and not an \fIinteger()\fR\&)\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
Two Erlang terms \fIcompare equal\fR\& if they either are of the same type and value, or if both are numeric types and extend to the same value, so that \fI1\fR\& compares equal to both \fI1\fR\& and \fI1\&.0\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
The \fIordered_set\fR\& works on the \fIErlang term order\fR\& and no defined order exists between an \fIinteger()\fR\& and a \fIfloat()\fR\& that extends to the same value\&. Hence the key \fI1\fR\& and the key \fI1\&.0\fR\& are regarded as equal in an \fIordered_set\fR\& table\&.
.LP
.RE

.SH "FAILURES"

.LP
Functions in this module fail by raising an error exception with error reason:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\fIbadarg\fR\&:
If any argument has the wrong format\&.
.TP 2
.B
\fIbadarg\fR\&:
If the table identifier is invalid\&.
.TP 2
.B
\fIbadarg\fR\&:
If the operation is denied because of table access rights (protected or private)\&.
.TP 2
.B
\fIsystem_limit\fR\&:
Modification of a value causes it to not be representable internally in the VM\&. For example, incrementation of a counter past the largest integer representable\&.
.TP 2
.B
\fIsystem_limit\fR\&:
If a match specification passed as argument has excessive nesting which causes scheduler stack exhaustion for the scheduler that the calling process is executing on\&. Scheduler stack size can be configured when starting the runtime system\&.
.RE
.SH "CONCURRENCY"

.LP
This module provides some limited support for concurrent access\&. All updates to single objects are guaranteed to be both \fIatomic\fR\& and \fIisolated\fR\&\&. This means that an updating operation to a single object either succeeds or fails completely without any effect (atomicity) and that no intermediate results of the update can be seen by other processes (isolation)\&. Some functions that update many objects state that they even guarantee atomicity and isolation for the entire operation\&. In database terms the isolation level can be seen as "serializable", as if all isolated operations are carried out serially, one after the other in a strict order\&.
.SH "TABLE TRAVERSAL"

.LP
There are different ways to traverse through the objects of a table\&.
.RS 2
.TP 2
*
\fISingle-step\fR\& traversal one key at at time, using \fIfirst/1\fR\&, \fInext/2\fR\&, \fIlast/1\fR\& and \fIprev/2\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
Search with simple \fImatch patterns\fR\&, using \fImatch/1/2/3\fR\&, \fImatch_delete/2\fR\& and \fImatch_object/1/2/3\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
Search with more powerful \fImatch specifications\fR\&, using \fIselect/1/2/3\fR\&, \fIselect_count/2\fR\&, \fIselect_delete/2\fR\&, \fIselect_replace/2\fR\& and \fIselect_reverse/1/2/3\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
\fITable conversions\fR\&, using \fItab2file/2/3\fR\& and \fItab2list/1\fR\&\&.
.LP
.RE

.LP
None of these ways of table traversal will guarantee a consistent table snapshot if the table is also updated during the traversal\&. Moreover, traversals not done in a \fIsafe\fR\& way, on tables where keys are inserted or deleted during the traversal, may yield the following undesired effects:
.RS 2
.TP 2
*
Any key may be missed\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
Any key may be found more than once\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
The traversal may fail with \fIbadarg\fR\& exception if keys are deleted\&.
.LP
.RE

.LP
A table traversal is \fIsafe\fR\& if either
.RS 2
.TP 2
*
the table is of type \fIordered_set\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
the entire table traversal is done within one ETS function call\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
function \fIsafe_fixtable/2\fR\& is used to keep the table fixated during the entire traversal\&.
.LP
.RE

.LP

.RS -4
.B
Note:
.RE
Even though the access of a single object is always guaranteed to be atomic and isolated, each traversal through a table to find the next key is not done with such guarantees\&. This is often not a problem, but may cause rare subtle "unexpected" effects if a concurrent process inserts objects during a traversal\&. For example, consider one process doing
.LP
.nf

ets:new(t, [ordered_set, named_table]),
ets:insert(t, {1}),
ets:insert(t, {2}),
ets:insert(t, {3}),

.fi
.LP
A concurrent call to \fIets:first(t)\fR\&, done by another process, may then in rare cases return \fI2\fR\& even though \fI2\fR\& has never existed in the table ordered as the first key\&. In the same way, a concurrent call to \fIets:next(t, 1)\fR\& may return \fI3\fR\& even though \fI3\fR\& never existed in the table ordered directly after \fI1\fR\&\&.
.LP
Effects like this are improbable but possible\&. The probability will further be reduced (if not vanish) if table option \fIwrite_concurrency\fR\& is not enabled\&. This can also only be a potential concern for \fIordered_set\fR\& where the traversal order is defined\&.

.LP
Traversals using \fImatch\fR\& and \fIselect\fR\& functions may not need to scan the entire table depending on how the key is specified\&. A match pattern with a \fIfully bound key\fR\& (without any match variables) will optimize the operation to a single key lookup without any table traversal at all\&. For \fIordered_set\fR\& a \fIpartially bound key\fR\& will limit the traversal to only scan a subset of the table based on term order\&. A partially bound key is either a list or a tuple with a prefix that is fully bound\&. Example:
.LP
.nf

1> T = ets:new(t,[ordered_set]), ets:insert(T, {"555-1234", "John Smith"})\&.
true
2> %% Efficient search of all with area code 555
2> ets:match(T,{[$5,$5,$5,$- |\&'$1\&'],\&'$2\&'})\&.
[["1234","John Smith"]]

.fi
.SH "MATCH SPECIFICATIONS"

.LP
Some of the functions use a \fImatch specification\fR\&, \fImatch_spec\fR\&\&. For a brief explanation, see \fIselect/2\fR\&\&. For a detailed description, see section  Match Specifications in Erlang in ERTS User\&'s Guide\&.
.LP
A match specifications with excessive nesting will cause a \fIsystem_limit\fR\& error exception to be raised\&.
