The specified \fIKey\fR\& is used to identify the object by either \fImatching\fR\& the key of an object in a \fIset\fR\& table, or \fIcompare equal\fR\& to the key of an object in an \fIordered_set\fR\& table (for details on the difference, see \fIlookup/2\fR\& and \fInew/2\fR\&)\&.
.LP
The function fails with reason \fIbadarg\fR\& in the following situations:
.RS 2
.TP 2
*
The table type is not \fIset\fR\& or \fIordered_set\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
\fIPos\fR\& < 1\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
\fIPos\fR\& > object arity\&.
